s \u2013 \"[[Hurt (Nine Inch Nails song)|Hurt]]\" on ''We Walk the Line: A Celebration of the Music of Johnny Cash''\n*2012 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"That Time Of Night\" on ''Oh Michael, Look What You've Done: Friends Play Michael Chapman''\n*2012 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"The Farm\" on ''The Inner Flame: A Rainer Ptacek Tribute''\n*2012 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"Mississippi You're On My Mind\" on ''Quiet About It: A Tribute To Jesse Winchester''\n*2012 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"Whispering Pines\" on ''Love for Levon''\n*2012 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"House of Earth\" on ''Woody Guthrie at 100: Live at the Kennedy Center''\n*2013 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"Everything But the Truth\" (first version) on ''[[The Lone Ranger (soundtrack)#The Lone Ranger: Wanted \u2013 Music Inspired by the Film|The Lone Ranger: Wanted]]''\n*2013 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"This Old Guitar\" on ''The Music Is You: A Tribute to John Denver''\n*2013 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013  \"Partners in Crime\" on ''Songs for Slim: Rockin' Here Tonight\u2014A Benefit Compilation for Slim Dunlap''\n*2014 \u2013 [[Chip Taylor]] \u2013 \"Sleep with Open Windows\" and \"I'll Only Be Me Once\" on ''The Little Prayers Trilogy''\n*2014 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"The Pretender\" on ''Looking into You: A Tribute To Jackson Browne''\n*2015 \u2013 Buick 6 \u2013 \"So Much Trouble in the World\" on ''Plays Well with Others''\n*2015 \u2013 [[G. Love & Special Sauce|G. Love and Special Sauce]] \u2013 \"New York City\" on ''Love Saves the Day''\n*2015 \u2013 [[Don Henley]] \u2013 \"Train in the Distance\" on ''[[Cass County (album)|Cass County]]''\n*2015 \u2013 [[Boz Scaggs]] \u2013 \"Whispering Pines\" (duet version) on ''A Fool to Care''\n*2015 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"Met an Old Friend\" on ''Remembering Mountains: Unheard Songs by Karen Dalton''\n*2016 \u2013 [[Buddy Miller]] \u2013 \"Hickory Wind\" (duet version) on ''Cayamo Sessions at Sea''\n*2016 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"It's Nobody's Fault But Mine\" and \"God Don't Never Change\" on ''God Don't Never Change: The Songs of Blind Willie Johnson''\n*2016 \u2013 Various Artists \u2013 \"Hickory Wind\" on ''The Life & Songs of Emmylou Harris''\n*2017 \u2013 [[Ray Wylie Hubbard]] \u2013 \"Tell the Devil I'm Getting There as Fast as I Can\" (also feat. [[Eric Church]]) on ''Tell the Devil I'm Getting There as Fast as I Can''\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===[[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]===\nThe Americana Awards are presented annually by the [[Americana Music Association]] and celebrate outstanding achievement in [[Americana (music)|americana]] music. Williams is one of the most nominated artists in the history of the awards show with 12, including 2 wins.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Category !! Nominated Work !! Result\n|-\n| 2003 || Artist of the Year || Lucinda Williams || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2003 || Song of the Year || Righteously || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2007 || Artist of the Year || Lucinda Williams || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2007 || Song of the Year || Are You Alright? || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2007 || Album of the Year || [[West (Lucinda Williams album)|West]] || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2011 || Lifetime Achievement Award <small>(songwriting)</small> || Lucinda Williams|| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2011 || Album of the Year || [[Blessed (Lucinda Williams album)|Blessed]] || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2015 || Song of the Year || \"East Side of Town\" || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2015 || Album of the Year || [[Down Where the Spirit Meets the Bone]] || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2015 || Artist of the Year || Lucinda Williams || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2016 || Artist of the Year || Lucinda Williams || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2016 || Album of the Year || [[The Ghosts of Highway 20]] || {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n===Grammy Awards===\nThe [[Grammy Award]]s are awarded annually by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] of the United States for outstanding achievements in the [[record industry]]. Williams has received three awards in three separate categories (country, folk and rock) from 15 nominations that span five genres (pop, rock, country, folk and Americana).\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Grammy Awards of 1993|1993]] || [[Passionate Kisses]] (songwriter \u2013 performed by [[Mary Chapin Carpenter]])<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9902/04/lucinda.williams/ \"Lucinda Williams chooses acclaim over fame any day\"]. ''[[CNN]]''. February 4, 1999.</ref><ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05E3DC133AF930A35750C0A962958260 \"The Grammy Winners\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. March 3, 1994.</ref> || [[Grammy Award for Best Country Song|Best Country Song]] || {{won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Grammy Awards of 1999|1999]] || \"Can't Let Go\" || [[Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance|Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Car Wheels on a Gravel Road]]<ref name=\"AMG\"/> || [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]] || {{won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"|[[44th Grammy Awards|2002]] || \"Essence\" || [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"Get Right with God\"<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1845783.stm \"Grammys 2002: The winners\"]. ''[[BBC News]]''. February 28, 2002.</ref> || Best Female Rock Vocal Performance || {{won}}\n|-\n| \"[[Cold, Cold Heart]]\" || [[Grammy Award for Best Female Country Vocal Performance|Best Female Country Vocal Performance]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Essence (Lucinda Williams album)|Essence]] || Best Contemporary Folk Album || {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[45th Grammy Awards|2003]] || \"Lately\" (from ''Going Driftless \u2013 An Artists' Tribute to Greg Brown'') || Best Female Country Vocal Performance ||  {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[46th Grammy Awards|2004]] || \"Righteously\" || Best Female Rock Vocal Performance || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[World Without Tears]] ||Best Contemporary Folk Album || {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[50th Grammy Awards|2008]] || rowspan=\"2\" | \"Come On\" || [[Grammy Award for Best Solo Rock Vocal Performance|Best Solo Rock Vocal Performance]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[52nd Grammy Awards|2010]] || [[Little Honey]] || [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]] ||  {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[53rd Grammy Awards|2011]] || \"Kiss Like Your Kiss\" (From ''[[True Blood]]'') || [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Song Written For Motion Picture, Television Or Other Visual Media]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[54th Grammy Awards|2012]] || [[Blessed (Lucinda Williams album)|Blessed]] || Best Americana Album ||  {{nom}}\n{{end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe American folk/rock band [[Augustana (band)|Augustana]] references the musician in the song \"Meet You There,\" on their studio album ''[[Can't Love, Can't Hurt]]''.  The lyrics state, \"Just put on Lucinda, Baby, and dance with me.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/meet-you-there-lyrics-augustana.html |last=Layus |first=Dan |title=Lyrics |work=Metro Lyrics |publisher=Sony |accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe is also referenced by the character Kathleen \"Kat\" Hall played by [[Mireille Enos]] in the film ''[[If I Stay (film)|If I Stay]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Music of Austin]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q256813|c=Category:Lucinda Williams|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no}}\n* {{official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0931200|name=Lucinda Williams}}\n* {{MusicBrainz artist|id=21685b15-3074-446e-aa1d-ff7157014f53|name=Lucinda Williams}}\n\n{{Lucinda Williams|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Lucinda}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Lake Charles, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Writers from Lake Charles, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American acoustic guitarists]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American alternative country singers]]\n[[Category:American female country singers]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Lost Highway Records artists]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:People with spina bifida]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Lucinda Williams| ]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucinda_Williams"}
{"title_page": "Cantharoid beetles", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| name = Cantharoid beetles\n| image =  Photuris lucicrescens.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Photuris lucicrescens]]''<ref>Cirrus Digital [http://www.cirrusimage.com/beetle_firefly_Photuris_lucicrescens.htm Firefly ''Photuris lucicrescens'']</ref>\n| image_alt = Photuris lucicrescens\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[beetle|Coleoptera]]\n| subordo = [[Polyphaga]]\n| infraordo = [[Elateriformia]]\n| superfamilia = '''Elateroidea'''\n| superfamilia_authority = [[William Elford Leach|Leach]], 1815\n| subdivision_ranks = Families\n| subdivision = \n10, see [[#Families|text]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Cantharoid beetles''' are a deprecated non-monophyletic taxonomic grouping (formerly superfamily Cantharoidea<ref name=\"Crowson1972\">{{cite journal|journal=Revista Univ Madr |last1=Crowson |first1=R.A. |date=1972 |title=A review of the classification of Cantharoidea (Coleoptera), with the definition of two new families, Cneoglossidae and Omethidae.|volume=21 |pages=35\u201377}}</ref>) within the currently accepted superfamily [[Elateroidea]].\n\n== Families<ref name=\"Parker1982\">{{cite book|author=Sybil P. Parker|title=Synopsis and classification of living organisms|url=https://archive.org/details/synopsisclassifi01park|url-access=registration|year=1982|publisher=McGraw-Hill|isbn=978-0-07-079031-5}}</ref> ==\n* [[Lampyridae]] \u2013 firefly beetles\n* [[Rhagophthalmidae]] \u2013 Asian starworms\n* [[Phengodidae]] LeConte 1861 \u2013 glowworm beetles (including Telegeusidae)\n* [[Brachypsectridae]] <small>Leconte & Horn, 1883</small> \u2013 Texas beetles\n* [[Cneoglossidae]] (Now in Superfamily [[Byrrhoidea]])\n* [[Omalisidae]] Lacordaire, 1857 (= Homalisidae, Omalysidae)\n* [[Lycidae]] \u2013 net-winged beetles\n* [[Drilidae]] <small>Blanchard, 1845</small>\n* [[Omethidae]] <small>LeConte, 1861</small> \u2013 [[false firefly beetle]]s\n* [[Cantharidae]] \u2013 soldier beetles (including Chauliognathidae)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Coleoptera|4}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4212620}}\n\n[[Category:Elateroidea| ]]\n[[Category:Obsolete arthropod taxa]]\n[[Category:Insect common names]]\n\n\n{{Elateroidea-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| name = Cantharoid beetles\n| image =  Photuris lucicrescens.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Photuris lucicrescens]]''<ref>Cirrus Digital [http://www.cirrusimage.com/beetle_firefly_Photuris_lucicrescens.htm Firefly ''Photuris lucicrescens'']</ref>\n| image_alt = Photuris lucicrescens\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[beetle|Coleoptera]]\n| subordo = [[Polyphaga]]\n| infraordo = [[Elateriformia]]\n| superfamilia = '''Elateroidea'''\n| superfamilia_authority = [[William Elford Leach|Leach]], 1815\n| subdivision_ranks = Families\n| subdivision = \n10, see [[#Families|text]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Cantharoid beetles''' are a deprecated taxonomic grouping (formerly superfamily Cantharoidea<ref name=\"Crowson1972\">{{cite journal|journal=Revista Univ Madr |last1=Crowson |first1=R.A. |date=1972 |title=A review of the classification of Cantharoidea (Coleoptera), with the definition of two new families, Cneoglossidae and Omethidae.|volume=21 |pages=35\u201377}}</ref>) within the currently accepted superfamily [[Elateroidea]].\n\n== Families<ref name=\"Parker1982\">{{cite book|author=Sybil P. Parker|title=Synopsis and classification of living organisms|url=https://archive.org/details/synopsisclassifi01park|url-access=registration|year=1982|publisher=McGraw-Hill|isbn=978-0-07-079031-5}}</ref> ==\n* [[Lampyridae]] \u2013 firefly beetles\n* [[Rhagophthalmidae]] \u2013 Asian starworms\n* [[Phengodidae]] LeConte 1861 \u2013 glowworm beetles (including Telegeusidae)\n* [[Brachypsectridae]] <small>Leconte & Horn, 1883</small> \u2013 Texas beetles\n* [[Cneoglossidae]] (Now in Superfamily [[Byrrhoidea]])\n* [[Omalisidae]] Lacordaire, 1857 (= Homalisidae, Omalysidae)\n* [[Lycidae]] \u2013 net-winged beetles\n* [[Drilidae]] <small>Blanchard, 1845</small>\n* [[Omethidae]] <small>LeConte, 1861</small> \u2013 [[false firefly beetle]]s\n* [[Cantharidae]] \u2013 soldier beetles (including Chauliognathidae)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Coleoptera|4}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4212620}}\n\n[[Category:Elateroidea| ]]\n[[Category:Obsolete arthropod taxa]]\n[[Category:Insect common names]]\n\n\n{{Elateroidea-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Photocyte", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantharoid_beetles"}
{"title_page": "Iran-Turkmenistan border", "text_new": "The '''Iran-Turkmenistan border ''' is 1,148km (713 miles) in length and runs from the [[Caspian Sea]] to the tripoint with [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html|title=CIA World Factbook - Iran |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> The Turkmen capital [[Ashgabat]] is only 15 miles north of this boundary, and [[Mashhad]] (Iran\u2019s second largest city) is 47 miles south of it.\n[[Image:Turkmenistan-map.png|thumb|350px|Map of Turkmenistan with Iran to the south]]\n\n==Description==\nThe border starts at the Caspian coast just to the south of the Turkmen town of [[Esenguly]]. It then goes overland in an eastwards directions in a series of straight lines through barren salt flats for 50km (31m) until reaching the [[Atrek]] river, the course of which it follows for 124km (77m) to a point just south of the Turkmen village of Chat.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> The border then continues overland eastwards/north-eastwards across the [[Kopet Dag]] mountain range for 151km (94m) before reaching the [[Sumbar River|Sumbar river]], the course of which it then follows for 41km (26m).<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> It then continues overland across mountain ridges in a broadly south-eastern arc for 455km (283m) to the vicinity of the Iranian village of [[Chahchaheh]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> From here a roughly straight line section runs for 77km (48m) to the [[Hari (Afghanistan)|Harirud river]] (Tedzhen in Turkmen), the course of which it follows south for 120km (75m) to the Afghan tripoint.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe immediate border area is largely uninhabited, except for the central section around Ashgabat on the Turkmen side; this area of the border, plus the western section, is roughly paralleled by highways. The Turkmen section of the [[Trans-Caspian Railway]] also roughly parallels the frontier in the central section, coming less than half a mile north of the boundary in the vicinity of [[Lotfabad]]. On the Iranian side, roughly 50 miles south of the border runs the major highways connecting the towns of [[Gorgan]], [[Bojnurd]] and [[Mashhad]], with roads connecting the smaller towns to the north.\n\n==History==\nThe border was inherited from the old Persia-USSR border, which largely took its current shape during the 19th Century after the [[Russian conquest of Central Asia]] and its annexation of the [[Khanate of Kokand]] and the [[Emirate of Bukhara]] in 1865-68. In 1869 Persia and Russia agreed that the Atrek river would be the border between them.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite |url= http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/boundaries-ii|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica \u2013 Border with Russia |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> This boundary was confirmed and then extended eastwards to the vicinity of Ashgabat in 1881 following further Russian advances into Turkmen lands, and then to the border with Afghanistan in 1893; various further delimitations of this border occurred in the following years.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite |url= http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/boundaries-ii|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica \u2013 Border with Russia |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> Further small changes were made in the period 1954-57 when Iran and the USSR (as they now were) agreed to more clearly demarcate their common border, including the Atrek delta region which had since altered due to the shrinking of the Caspian Sea.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Border crossings==\n* Bajgiran (IRN) \u2013 Bajgiran (TKM) (road)<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/turkmenistan/#turkmenistan-iran-border-crossings |title=Caravanistan \u2013 Iran-Turkmenistan border crossings |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Sarakhs (IRN) \u2013 Serakhs (TKM) (road)<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/turkmenistan/#turkmenistan-iran-border-crossings |title=Caravanistan \u2013 Iran-Turkmenistan border crossings |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Lotfabad (IRN) \u2013 Artyk (TKM) (road)<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/turkmenistan/#turkmenistan-iran-border-crossings |title=Caravanistan \u2013 Iran-Turkmenistan border crossings |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Settlements near the border==\n===Iran===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Gomishan]]\n* [[Incheh Borun]]\n* Bachcheh Darreh\n* [[Hesarcheh]]\n* [[Robat, Zavin]]\n* [[Shuy, Razavi Khorasan]]\n* [[Lotfabad]]\n* [[Now Khandan]]\n* [[Dargaz]]\n* [[Khakestar]]\n* Giru\n* Koshtani\n* [[Qarah Takan, Razavi Khorasan]]\n* [[Chahchaheh]]\n* Alamtu\n* [[Sarakhs]]\n* [[Shir Tappeh]]\n* [[Jannatabad, Torbat-e Jam]]\n{{div col end}}\n===Turkmenistan===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Esenguly]]\n* Ajyyap\n* [[Gyzyletrek]]\n* Chat\n* Kuruzhdey\n* [[Khodzhakala]]\n* K\u00ebnekesir\n* Shemli\n* Kazgan\n* Arab-Kala\n* Hawdan\n* [[Kaka, Turkmenistan|Kaka]]\n* [[Dushak]]\n* [[Miana, Turkmenistan|Miana]]\n* Imeni Kuliyev\n* [[Akhchadepe]]\n* Karaman Vtoroy\n* Kichiga Vtoraya\n* [[Serakhs]]\n* Polekhatum\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Iran-Turkmenistan relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Borders of Iran}}\n{{Borders of Turkmenistan}}\n\n[[Category:Borders of Iran]]\n[[Category:Borders of Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Iran-Turkmenistan border ''' is 1,148km (713 miles) in length and runs from the [[Caspian Sea]] to the tripoint with [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html|title=CIA World Factbook - Iran |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> The Turkmen capital [[Ashgabat]] is only 15 miles north of this boundary, and [[Mashhad]] (Iran\u2019s second largest city) is 47 miles south of it.\n[[Image:Turkmenistan-map.png|thumb|350px|Map of Turkmenistan with Iran to the south]]\n\n==Description==\nThe border starts at the Caspian coast just to the south of the Turkmen town of [[Esenguly]]. It then goes overland in an eastwards directions in a series of straight lines through barren salt flats for 50km (31m) until reaching the [[Atrek]] river, the course of which it follows for 124km (77m) to a point just south of the Turkmen village of Chat.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> The border then continues overland eastwards/north-eastwards across the [[Kopet Dag]] mountain range for 151km (94m) before reaching the [[Sumbar River|Sumbar river]], the course of which it then follows for 41km (26m).<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> It then continues overland across mountain ridges in a broadly south-eastern arc for 455km (283m) to the vicinity of the Iranian village of [[Chahchaheh]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> From here a roughly straight line section runs for 77km (48m) to the [[Hari (Afghanistan)|Harirud river]] (Tedzhen in Turkmen), the course of which it follows south for 120km (75m) to the Afghan tripoint.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe immediate border area is largely uninhabited, except for the central section around Ashgabat on the Turkmen side; this area of the border, plus the western section, is roughly paralleled by highways. The Turkmen section of the [[Trans-Caspian Railway]] also roughly parallels the frontier in the central section, coming less than half a mile north of the boundary in the vicinity of [[Lotfabad]]. On the Iranian side, roughly 50 miles south of the border runs the major highways connecting the towns of [[Gorgan]], [[Bojnurd]] and [[Mashhad]], with roads connecting the smaller towns to the north.\n\n==History==\nThe border was inherited from the old Persia-USSR border, which largely took its current shape during the 19th Century after the [[Russian conquest of Central Asia]] and its annexation of the [[Khanate of Kokand]] and the [[Emirate of Bukhara]] in 1865-68. In 1869 Persia and Russia agreed that the Atrek river would be the border between them.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite |url= http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/boundaries-ii|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica \u2013 Border with Russia |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> This boundary was confirmed and then extended eastwards to the vicinity of Ashgabat in 1881 following further Russian advances into Turkmen lands, and then to the border with Afghanistan in 1893; various further delimitations of this border occurred in the following years.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite |url= http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/boundaries-ii|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica \u2013 Border with Russia |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref> Further small changes were made in the period 1954-57 when Iran and the USSR (as they now were) agreed to more clearly demarcate their common border, including the Atrek delta region which had since altered due to the shrinking of the Caspian Sea.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite |url= http://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 - Iran-USSR Boundary|date=28 February 1978|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Border crossings==\n* Bajgiran (IRN) \u2013 Bajgiran (TKM) (road)<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/turkmenistan/#turkmenistan-iran-border-crossings |title=Caravanistan \u2013 Iran-Turkmenistan border crossings |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Sarakhs (IRN) \u2013 Serakhs (TKM) (road)<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/turkmenistan/#turkmenistan-iran-border-crossings |title=Caravanistan \u2013 Iran-Turkmenistan border crossings |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Lotfabad (IRN) \u2013 Artyk (TKM) (road)<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/turkmenistan/#turkmenistan-iran-border-crossings |title=Caravanistan \u2013 Iran-Turkmenistan border crossings |access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Settlements near the border==\n===Iran===\n* [[Gomishan]]\n* [[Incheh Borun]]\n* Bachcheh Darreh\n* [[Hesarcheh]]\n* [[Robat, Zavin]]\n* [[Shuy, Razavi Khorasan]]\n* [[Lotfabad]]\n* [[Now Khandan]]\n* [[Dargaz]]\n* [[Khakestar]]\n* Giru\n* Koshtani\n* [[Qarah Takan, Razavi Khorasan]]\n* [[Chahchaheh]]\n* Alamtu\n* [[Sarakhs]]\n* [[Shir Tappeh]]\n* [[Jannatabad, Torbat-e Jam]]\n===Turkmenistan===\n* [[Esenguly]]\n* Ajyyap\n* [[Gyzyletrek]]\n* Chat\n* Kuruzhdey\n* [[Khodzhakala]]\n* K\u00ebnekesir\n* Shemli\n* Kazgan\n* Arab-Kala\n* Hawdan\n* [[Kaka, Turkmenistan|Kaka]]\n* [[Dushak]]\n* [[Miana, Turkmenistan|Miana]]\n* Imeni Kuliyev\n* [[Akhchadepe]]\n* Karaman Vtoroy\n* Kichiga Vtoraya\n* [[Serakhs]]\n* Polekhatum\n\n==See also==\n* [[Iran-Turkmenistan relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Borders of Iran}}\n{{Borders of Turkmenistan}}\n\n[[Category:Borders of Iran]]\n[[Category:Borders of Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "name_user": "WisDom-UK", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSettlements near the border", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iran-Turkmenistan_border"}
{"title_page": "Subterranean (EP)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Subterranean\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[In Flames]]\n| cover      = In Flames - Subterranean.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 15 June 1995\n| recorded   = November-December 1994\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Studio Fredman]]\n| genre      = [[Melodic death metal]]\n| length     = 20:50\n| label      = [[Wrong Again Records|Wrong Again]]\n| producer   = [[In Flames]]\n| prev_title = [[Lunar Strain]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[The Jester Race]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r506815|pure_url=yes}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Subterranean''''' is the first [[Extended play|EP]] by [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[heavy metal music|metal]] band [[In Flames]], released on 15 June 1995. It was remastered and re-released in 2003 by [[Regain Records]] and reissued again in 2014, featuring additional tracks.\n\n\"Dead Eternity\" is featured on the album ''[[The Jester Race]]'', with [[Anders Frid\u00e9n]] as the vocalist. \"The Inborn Lifeless\" is also featured in this album, but with a different name (\"Dead God in Me\"), lyrics, an alternate ending, and a slightly different solo. Although drummer [[Daniel Erlandsson]] is pictured with the band through certain parts of the EP, he was only a guest, and did not perform on the EP.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Stand Ablaze\n| length1 = 4:33\n| title2 = Everdying\n| length2 = 4:23\n| title3 = Subterranean\n| length3 = 5:46\n| title4 = Timeless (Instrumental)\n| length4 = 1:46\n| title5 = Biosphere\n| length5 = 5:07\n}}\n<br>\n{{tracklist\n| headline = 2014 reissue\n| collapsed = yes\n| title6 = Dead Eternity\n| length6 = 5:01\n| title7 = The Inborn Lifeless\n| length7 = 3:23\n| title8 = [[Eye of the Beholder (song)|Eye of the Beholder]]\n| note8 = [[Metallica]] cover\n| length8 = 5:32\n| title9 = Murders in the Rue Morgue\n| note9 = [[Iron Maiden]] cover\n| length9 = 3:07 \n|all_writing=|title1=|length1=|title2=|length2=|title3=|length3=|title4=|length4=|title5=|length5=|title10=|length10=|title11=|length11=|title12=|length12=|title13=|length13=|title14=|length14=|title15=|length15=|title16=|length16=|title17=|length17=|title18=|length18=|title19=|length19=|title20=|length20=|total_length=}}\n\n==Credits==\n\n===In Flames===\n*[[Henke Forss]] \u2013 [[singing|vocals]], lyrics \n*[[Jesper Str\u00f6mblad]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]]s, [[acoustic guitars]]\n*[[Glenn Ljungstr\u00f6m]] \u2013 lead guitars\n*[[Johan Larsson (musician)|Johann Larsson]] \u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]]\n\n===Guests===\n*Jocke G\u00f6tberg \u2013 vocals on \"Dead Eternity\"\n*Per Gyllenb\u00e4ck \u2013 vocals on \"The Inborn Lifeless\"\n*Robert Dahne \u2013 vocals on \"Eye of the Beholder\"\n*[[Anders Frid\u00e9n]] \u2013 vocals on \"Murders in the Rue Morgue\"<ref>http://www.discogs.com/In-Flames-Colony/release/5030665</ref>\n*[[Oscar Dronjak]] \u2013 [[backing vocals]] on \"Stand Ablaze\"\n*[[Daniel Erlandsson]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]] on tracks 1, 2, 6-9\n*[[Anders Jivarp]] \u2013 drums on tracks 3, 5\n\n==Other personnel==\n*Engineered by [[Fredrik Nordstr\u00f6m]].\n*Mastered by Staffan Olofsson.\n*Cover art and photos by [[Kenneth Johansson]].\n*Layout by Dennis Jernberg.\n*[[James Hetfield]] \u2013 [[songwriter]] on \"Eye of the Beholder\"\n*[[Lars Ulrich]] \u2013 [[music composition|music]] on \"Eye of the Beholder\"\n*[[Kirk Hammett]] \u2013 music on \"Eye of the Beholder\n*[[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] \u2013 songwriter on \"Murders in the Rue Morgue\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.discogs.com/In-Flames-Subterranean/master/28341 ''Subterranean'' releases information on discogs] \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061108091336/http://www.inflames.com/releases/albums/subterranean/default.asp ''Subterranean'' album details]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061019224811/http://www.inflames.com/releases/albums/subterranean/info.html ''Subterranean'' information]\n\n{{In Flames}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Subterranean (Ep)}}\n[[Category:In Flames albums]]\n[[Category:1995 EPs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Subterranean\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[In Flames]]\n| cover      = In Flames - Subterranean.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 15 June 1995\n| recorded   = November-December 1994\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Studio Fredman]]\n| genre      = [[Melodic death metal]]\n| length     = 20:50\n| label      = [[Wrong Again Records|Wrong Again]]\n| producer   = [[In Flames]]\n| prev_title = [[Lunar Strain]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[The Jester Race]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r506815|pure_url=yes}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Subterranean''''' is the first [[Extended play|EP]] by [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[heavy metal music|metal]] band [[In Flames]], released on 15 June 1995. It was remastered and re-released in 2003 by [[Regain Records]] and reissued again in 2014, featuring additional tracks.\n\n\"Dead Eternity\" is featured on the album ''[[The Jester Race]]'', with [[Anders Frid\u00e9n]] as the vocalist. \"The Inborn Lifeless\" is also featured in this album, but with a different name (\"Dead God in Me\"), lyrics, an alternate ending, and a slightly different solo. Although drummer [[Daniel Erlandsson]] is pictured with the band through certain parts of the EP, he was only a guest, and did not perform on the EP.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Stand Ablaze\n| length1 = 4:33\n| title2 = Everdying\n| length2 = 4:23\n| title3 = Subterranean\n| length3 = 5:46\n| title4 = Timeless (Instrumental)\n| length4 = 1:46\n| title5 = Biosphere\n| length5 = 5:07\n}}\n<br>\n{{tracklist\n| headline = 2014 Reissue\n| collapsed = yes\n| title6 = Dead Eternity\n| length6 = 5:01\n| title7 = The Inborn Lifeless\n| length